In [17]:
app_data['Price']= app_data['Price'].apply(lambda x: str(x).replace('$','')if '$'in str(x) else str(x))
app_data['Price']= app_data['Price'].apply(lambda x :float(x))
app_data['Reviews']= app_data['Reviews'].apply(lambda x:int(x))
app_data['Installs']= app_data['Installs'].apply(lambda x: str(x).replace('+','')if '+'in str(x) else str(x))
app_data['Installs']= app_data['Installs'].apply(lambda x:str(x).replace(',','')if ','in str(x) else str(x))
app_data['Installs']= app_data['Installs'].apply(lambda x: float(x))
app_data['Size']=app_data['Size'].apply(lambda x : str(x).replace('M','')if 'M'in str(x)else str(x))
app_data['Size']= pd.to_numeric(app_data['Size'],errors='coerce')
app_data['Size']= app_data['Size'].apply(lambda x: float(x)*1000)
In [18]:
app_data['Size']= app_data['Size'].fillna(app_data['Size'].mean())

Bivariate Analysis-:¶

Make scatter plot/joinplot for Rating vs. Price-:¶

In [43]:
app_data_dropped = app_data[app_data['Price'] <200]

app_data_dropped
app_data_dropped.plot(kind='scatter', x='Rating', y='Price')
plt.show()

Observation-:¶

The pattern we can observe from the above plot is that price has not direct effect on rating.¶

On the other hand free apps and apps with lower price are much high on ratings.¶

Make scatter plot/joinplot for Rating vs. Size-:¶

In [44]:
app_data_dropped.plot(kind='scatter', x='Rating', y='Size')
plt.show()

Observation-:¶

As observed above apps larger in Size have good ratings as compared to apps of smaller size.¶

Hence, size is highly related to rating.¶

Apps having more reviews are higher in rating as compared to apps with less reviews.¶
